6, 2018)</Para></Corrections><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>A lawsuit in Connecticut against a leading maker of AR-15 rifles is awaiting a pivotal court ruling over whether the gun industry can be held legally responsible for mass shootings.</Para><Para>The Connecticut Supreme Court is deciding whether to throw out a wrongful-death lawsuit brought by families of victims killed at Sandy Hook Elementary School against the manufacturer of the semiautomatic gun Adam Lanza used in the 2012 rampage.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Deploying a novel tort theory in pursuit of damages, plaintiffs' lawyers for the families are trying to overcome a 2005 federal law that gives firearm sellers and manufacturers protection from liability claims over gun violence.</Para><Para>The gun-control movement—intensifying after <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shooting-at-florida-high-school-authorities-report-1518638881">last month's school shooting in Parkland, Fla.,</ELink> which left 17 people dead—has mostly focused on legislation, with student activists pressing federal and state lawmakers to pass tighter restrictions.</Para><Para>A reversal by the Connecticut court could offer victims of other shootings a legal road map for establishing liability against an industry that has faced little legal threat for more than a decade. If the case is allowed to proceed, it could also expose the industry's marketing practices to more scrutiny.</Para><Para>Litigation by gun-control advocates in recent years has lost ground to lobbying as a preferred strategy. In the late 1990s and early 2000s, particularly after <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-gift-no-school-wants-to-receive-1519578001">the school shooting in Columbine, Colo.,</ELink> the gun industry faced a wave of lawsuits from shooting victims and municipalities over criminal misuse of its products.</Para><Para>Echoing the legal assault against the tobacco industry, cases against gun companies ran the gamut from public nuisance suits to complaints blaming gun violence on a "negligent oversupply" of weapons. Few of the suits had progressed far by the time the Republican-led Congress passed the Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act, or PLCAA, in 2005.</Para><Para>"The PLCAA basically slowed lawsuits against gun sellers to a trickle," said Georgia State University law professor Timothy D. Lytton, who wrote a book about gun litigation.</Para><Para>The National Rifle Association, which led the lobbying effort, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.nraila.org/articles/20050729/joint-statement-by-nra-executive-vice-p">trumpeted</ELink> its passage as a death knell for "politically motivated predatory lawsuits."</Para><Para>The late Sen. Ted Kennedy, a Massachusetts Democrat, thundered against it, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CREC-2005-07-28/html/CREC-2005-07-28-pt1-PgS9208.htm">calling </ELink>the PLCAA an "unprecedented interference with the judicial branch of government" that would deny "victims their day in court."</Para><Para>Prior to the law's passage, more than 30 states had passed bills barring municipality-led lawsuits or giving dealers and manufacturers near-blanket immunity from liability. The PLCAA expanded the immunity nationwide, carving out small exceptions, which are at the heart of the Sandy Hook lawsuit.</Para><Para>Plaintiffs in Connecticut have seized on a provision allowing for lawsuits against gun sellers based on "negligent entrustment," the same legal doctrine that can find someone liable for allowing a visibly drunk person to use their car.</Para><Para>In court briefs, the Sandy Hook families contend Remington Outdoor Co., the owner of the Bushmaster rifle brand, negligently entrusted and marketed "military style" weapons to a young demographic, targeting "video-game playing, military-obsessed 18-year-olds like Adam Lanza."</Para><Para>A trial court judge dismissed the lawsuit in 2016 before the case ever entered the evidence phase. The plaintiffs then appealed to Connecticut's high court.</Para><Para>Gun retailers have been found liable for selling a gun to a visibly drunk buyer or to a so-called straw buyer, knowing the customer is buying the weapon on behalf of someone banned from purchase. But no court has held a company liable for releasing a gun into a distribution channel that is several transactions removed from a potential perpetrator of gun violence.</Para><Para>Lawyers for Remington say it doesn't make sense to blame the company for entrusting Adam Lanza with a gun. They say the company knew nothing about Lanza, who acquired the weapon from his mother, before the massacre that left 26 dead, including 20 children.</Para><Para>A negligent entrustment claim can't be established without showing that a firearm seller "knew or was given a reason to know that the buyer is likely to use the product to cause harm," said James Vogts, a lawyer for Remington.</Para><Para><ELink type="webpage" ref="http://www.ct-n.com/ctnplayer.asp?odID=14744">Arguing</ELink> before Connecticut Supreme Court justices in November, Mr. Vogts said it is almost impossible for a gun company high up the supply chain to be liable for a shooting.</Para><Para>He stated that what plaintiffs are really arguing is that "civilians at large are not competent to use this gun."</Para><Para>Plaintiffs' lead counsel Josh Koskoff argued that Remington's pursuit of youthful customers is the link between the company and Lanza. "Remington may never have known Adam Lanza, but they had been courting him for years," he told the bench.</Para><Para>He also referred the judges to a 1977 Michigan Supreme Court ruling involving negligent entrustment that found that a maker of a high-powered slingshot could be held liable for encouraging children to buy its product.</Para><Para>Prof. David M. Studdert, a health-policy researcher at Stanford Law School, said the lawsuit against Remington has always faced long odds.</Para><Para>The National Rifle Association calls the AR-15 "the most popular rifle in America," estimating that millions of Americans own at least one. "Virtually all of them are used for lawful purposes," said Prof. Studdert.</Para><Para>That makes it hard, he said, to prove that Remington "knew or reasonably should have known that the gun sold to Mrs. Lanza would be used in a mass shooting."</Para><Para>Prof. Lytton in Georgia said a reversal reviving the lawsuit—particularly in such a case with national implications—would stand a good chance at getting reviewed by U.S. Supreme Court.</Para><Para>Write to Jacob Gershman at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:jacob.gershman@wsj.com">jacob.gershman@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Jacob Gershman </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-court-case-making-gun-makers-anxious-1521192601" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

